  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Reflect</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This project shifted your relationship with the database. It went from a container you run to infrastructure you operate. Ask yourself:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Managed vs self-hosted:</strong> What did RDS give you that a Docker container didn't? What did you give up (control, cost, flexibility)?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Migrations:</strong> Did Alembic change how you think about schema changes? Was reviewing migration SQL different from reviewing application code?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Blue/green deployment:</strong> How did it feel to deploy with zero downtime? What was the hardest part — the Terraform setup, the backward-compatible migrations, or the GitHub Actions pipeline?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Grafana dashboards:</strong> Were the dashboards useful during development, or only after deployment? What would you add to them?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Linear vs GitHub Projects:</strong> How did switching tools feel? Was the adjustment difficult, or did the workflow transfer naturally?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Point-in-time recovery:</strong> How did the recovery drill feel? Would you be confident running it under pressure if real data was at risk?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Data sensitivity:</strong> Did the medical data classification change how you built or tested anything? Did it influence infrastructure decisions?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The "show someone" moment</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Open three browser tabs and the Grafana dashboard. Show someone:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>The patient booking an appointment at a specific location — and the confirmation message</li>
    <li>The practitioner viewing their schedule and writing a clinical note with patient history visible</li>
    <li>The admin filtering by location and managing appointments across all three clinics</li>
    <li>The Grafana dashboard showing live metrics while the system is being used</li>
    <li>Then deploy a change via blue/green while someone is using the system — they don't notice</li>
    <li>Then show the RDS backup history — "I can restore this database to any point in the last 7 days"</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">"Three user types, three locations, medical data with automated backups, zero-downtime deployment, and I can see everything on a dashboard."</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Key insight:</strong> The database is the most important piece of infrastructure. If the application crashes, you redeploy. If the database is lost, the business is lost. Everything you built in this project — RDS, automated backups, migration rollbacks, point-in-time recovery, Grafana alerts — exists to protect and operate the database safely. The application is replaceable. The data is not.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: observability</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">We use Grafana with CloudWatch as a data source. Here's the broader observability landscape.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Grafana + Prometheus</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Prometheus is a time-series database that scrapes metrics from your application. Grafana visualises them. The open-source standard for metrics and dashboards. We use Grafana with CloudWatch instead of Prometheus, but the dashboarding skills are identical.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Grafana + Loki</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Loki is a log aggregation system by the Grafana team. Like Prometheus but for logs. Cheaper than Elasticsearch because it indexes labels, not content. Pair with Grafana for a unified metrics + logs view.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Datadog</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">All-in-one observability platform. Metrics, logs, traces, dashboards, alerting. SaaS — no infrastructure to manage. Powerful but expensive at scale. Popular with startups and mid-size companies.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">New Relic</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Application Performance Monitoring (APM) with dashboards and alerting. Strong at tracing individual requests through the system. Generous free tier for small projects.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">OpenTelemetry</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Not a platform — a standard. An open specification for collecting metrics, logs, and traces. Vendor-neutral: instrument your code once, send data to any backend (Grafana, Datadog, New Relic). The industry is converging on this as the standard instrumentation layer.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">AWS CloudWatch</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use as a data source. AWS-native monitoring with automatic metrics for all AWS services. Good for infrastructure metrics, less flexible for custom application metrics. We visualise it through Grafana rather than the CloudWatch console because Grafana provides a better dashboard experience.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">The observability stack is converging: OpenTelemetry for instrumentation, Prometheus or a cloud backend for metrics storage, Grafana for visualisation. Datadog and New Relic bundle everything into one platform — the trade-off is cost vs. operational simplicity. For learning, Grafana + CloudWatch teaches the concepts without the cost.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

